Motivation

  • perception of Gen Z as very politicizedâ but not always the way we expect
  • (party) mobilization of young voters as an ongoing challenge

Overview

  • â Question: Can parties mobilize young people by sending letters to first-time voters?
  • ð¡ Expectation: Positive effect because letters cut through the noise of other omnipresent forms of communication
  • ï¸âï¸ Data & Method:
    • field experiment with a German parliamentary party
    • randomized distribution of 37,000 letters
  • ð Results:
    • no effect on turnout or vote share on the aggregate level
    • findings supported by a post-election survey

Literature & Expectations

  • experimental GOTV literature from US finds campaigns to be impactful, but effect sizes vary by target audience (Gerber & Green, 2019)
  • younger cohorts might be less responsive to traditional mail (Kalla & Broockman, 2018), but tailored messages can be persuasive (Malhotra et al., 2011)

Expectation:

  • Positive effect on turnout as well as party vote share
  • tailored, direct letter might âcut through the noiseâ

Design âï¸

  • field experiment with a German parliamentary party
  • conducted in one federal state before the 2024 European elections
  • treatment
    • 37,000 letters to first-voters (140,000)
    • randomized distribution by ZIP-code, blocked by state district
    • content: election info, whatâs at stake, mail-vote how-to
  • post-election survey with 1,400 respondents

Estimation ð

  • aggregate analysis of election results:
    • geospatial match of ZIP-codes with election districts
    • hypothesis test by randomization inference
  • individual-level survey analysis:
    • OLS with heteroscedasticity robust standard errors

Aggregate Results

  • neither effect on turnout nor party vote share in treated election districts
  • no impact on overall election outcomes

Survey results

  • no effect on turnout or party choice among surveyed first voters either

Mechanisms

  • similarly, no evidence that the treatment impacted any of the proposed mechanisms

Caveat: Low recall

  • only 37% of treated respondents remember receiving a letter
  • robustness: limiting analysis to respondents who recall does not alter findings

Conclusion

  • no effect of direct-letter campaigns to first voters for the 2024 EP election
  • campaign costs better invested elsewhere
  • changing (communication) habits require a repeated re-evaluation of GOTV measures
